metadata.name: Cyanotypes #162
metadata.description:
This is an algorithmic tribute to the pioneering work of Anna Atkins (1799-1871). Considered by many the first female photographer, Atkins learned about the cyanotype process soon after it was invented by John Herschel, a family friend. As a botanist, she had the idea of using the new technique to produce contact prints of plants. Her investigations succeeded in capturing the nuances in morphology and the delicate details of many species.

In 1843 she published “British Algae: Cyanotype impressions”, the first published book to use a photographic process for the illustrations. Each copy gathered around 400 prints, each of them individually produced from a different specimen. Thus, all books featured the same species, but each of them was different, in a process that was itself generative in a certain way. Today, about 17 copies of the book are preserved in different institutions. Atkins went on to publish two more books in the following years, with the help of her friend Anne Dixon, dedicated to various ferns and plants.

“Cyanotypes” pays homage to her wonderful work, which sits at the intersection between science and art, and used technology in a novel way to capture the beauty of nature. Here things are taken one step forward, to generate algorithmic simulations of plants, ferns, and algae, which are the work of fantasy and not necessarily faithful to the traits of any real species.

The work features 28 basic configurations, each of them in turn capable of unlimited variations. As was the case with the prints from “British Algae”, every image is at the same time part of a series and unique. 

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 800 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be very slow.

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Over the hills... #32
metadata.description:
A flurry of shapes, waves and colors at the intersection of figurative and abstract.

Created with p5js using multiple shape primitives, gradient noise and various sine & cosine functions.

The algorithm contains multiple loops plotting several thousands of shapes and lines and may take up to 12 seconds to display the artwork.

Dutch action 10-8-6-4 at 10 minute intervals.

metadata.name: Fragment Assembler #132
metadata.description:
Fragment Assembler is a chaos engine that creates complex abstract patterns and textures. As the artwork is drawn, it constantly recomposes itself during assembly with a series of displacement techniques, creating new forms and visual elements, while others get broken into pieces and textures. The work is orientation agnostic, and will display the output in portrait orientation on tall displays.

Intended to display on high resolution mode. The artwork renders with lower resolution by default to maintain compatibility with lower end devices. 

Press '2' to double the internal resolution (recommended).
Press 'h' to enable full internal resolution (requires a modern desktop computer).
Press space bar to reload the work.
Press 's' to save the output as PNG.
To render a 6k PNG, first press 'h', then save with 'p' (requires a modern desktop computer).


Made with p5.js & WebGL.
Best displayed with a modern desktop system & Chrome browser. 


Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: AN2: Recuerdos  #81
metadata.description:
"AN2: Recuerdos" is an abstract collection that is the direct sequel to Artificialmente Natural. Recuerdos are memories in Spanish, and with this collection, I tried to evoke specifically that, a memory. There are many times throughout our life that our memory changes and grow. Sometimes we even alter memories unconsciously, mixing them up between other memories and even fantasy or dreams (ever had a Deja Vu?), creating a new memory solely based on an idea of the past and what it was. We live in a world of perceptions, and that is exactly what our memory is, a combination of perceptions that became ideas, made up of other older ideas and new ones, to then get stored inside our brain as new memories.

Now, you may ask, cool story, but what does it have to do with the collection? Well, through your memories, experiences, and perceptions, you're going to analyze the piece. You may think you see an abstract ocean in the background, or a sky, or waves, or auras. You may feel that the art piece sometimes looks decayed, splattered with paint, or just splattered with dirty noise. The truth is that through your memory, you're going to try to make sense of it no matter if you like what you're seeing or not, and that's the sole idea of everything. Interpreting through our experiences is how we calm the tension we feel from the unknown. You can't make a comparison or an interpretation if you haven't seen or experienced something that laid an idea inside your brain, becoming multiple other ideas through plasticity and neural connectivity, always trying to make sense of everything. That's why your "recuerdos" is the key to the way you interpret life and live it, both unconsciously and consciously. 

For me, this collection consciously reminds me of my teenage years. A little chaotic at times, with some beautiful moments of self-discovery. Mistakes were made, love was found and lost, and everything was pretty colorful and new. Unconsciously, I don't know, that's the beauty of the unknown. 

--------------------------------------------------------------

NOTICE

Allow list will be deleted 48 hours after the collections goes live.

--------------------------------------------------------------
FYI

Loading of the art goes through 3 stages in order. It may take between 30 seconds to 40 seconds to finalize.

-------------------------------------------------------------

Press [S] to save as PNG

metadata.name: Whisper #112
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: Brutal Infection #144
metadata.description:
Brutal Infection explores the concept of structural organisms from a dystopian vision.The use of muted colors reflects the cold and inhuman nature of the organisms, while also emphasizing the sense of evolution, emergence, and life within these structures.

The compositions are based on trigonometric functions, aligning geometric shapes into abstract forms, creating a sense of harmony and balance amidst the chaos and turmoil of the structural organisms.

The viewer is invited to examine the tiniest details, as they are the most interesting, alive, and emerging parts of the structures themselves.
___________________

Due to differences in how shaders operate in different engines, there may be slight differences between the preview image and the live-rendered output.

To obtain the live-rendered version, you can press the 's' key in live view or alternatively, you can right-click and save the preview image.

Made with p5js and glsl shaders.

Best experienced in fullscreen.
